back, sometimes evading it, sometimes deploying it strategically, to a variety of effects and consequences. The collection advances an understanding of sectarianism simultaneously constructed and experienced, a slippery and changeable concept with material effects. And even as the book's focus is Lebanon, its analysis fractures the association of sectarianism with the nation-state and suggests possibilities that can travel to other sites. Practicing Sectarianism, taken as a whole, argues that sectarianism can only be fully understood—and dismantled—if we first take it seriously as a practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCommunalismxReligious aspects. 0aCommunalismzLebanon. 0aSectsxPolitical aspectszLebanon. 0aSectsxSocial aspectszLebanon. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aLebanon.  aMiddle East.  aanthropology.  aeveryday.  ahistory.  asect.  asectarianism.  asocial practice.1 aArãş, Roxana Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailony, Reem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeeb, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeeb, Lara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMikdashi, Maya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNalbantian, Tsolin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNalbantian, Tsolin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSayed, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSbaiti, Nadya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSbaiti, Nadya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTsolin, Nalbantian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTit